    <title>Calculating the Physical Properties of an Exoplanet</title>
    <parts>
        <part type="statement">
            <p>
                <s>TRAPPIST-1e is an exoplanet that orbits the star TRAPPIST-1.</s>
                <s>The exoplanet orbits the star on a roughly circular orbit at a distance of
                <quantity><value>0.029</value><unit>astronomical_unit</unit></quantity>.</s>
            </p>
        </part>
        <part type="mcq" must_show_choices="false">
            <main_text>
                <p>
                    <s>Does TRAPPIST-1e orbit its star at a smaller or at a larger orbital radius than 
                Earth’s orbital radius around the Sun?</s>
                </p>
            </main_text>
            <response_formats>
                <response_format type="choices">
                    <choices>
                        <choice is_correct_answer="true">A smaller orbital radius</choice>
                        <choice>A larger orbital radius</choice>
                    </choices>
                </response_format>
            </response_formats>
            <solutions> 
                <solution>
                    <p>
                        <s>Recall that the astronomical unit, with the symbol <unit>astronomical_unit</unit>, is a unit of length 
                        approximately equal to the distance between the Earth and the Sun - the distance between the Earth and the Sun
                        is approximately <quantity><value>1</value><unit>astronomical_unit</unit></quantity>.</s>
                        <s>Therefore, if the distance between any planet and its host star is less than <quantity><value>1</value><unit>astronomical_unit</unit></quantity>,
                        it is closer to its host star than Earth is to the Sun.</s>
                    </p>
                </solution>
            </solutions>
            <marks>1</marks>
        </part>
        <part type="mcq" must_show_choices="false">
            <main_text>
                <p>
                    <s>Use the formula <m>T = \sqrt{\frac{4 \pi^{2} r^{3}}{GM}}</m>, where <m>r</m> 
                    is the radius of the exoplanet’s orbit, <m>M</m> is the mass of the host star, and 
                    <m>G</m> is the universal gravitational constant, to find <m>T</m>, the period of 
                    the exoplanet’s orbit.</s> 
                    <s>TRAPPIST-1 has a mass of <quantity><value>1.8 \times 10^{29}</value><unit>kilogram</unit></quantity>.</s>
                    <s>Use a value of <quantity><value>6.67 \times 10^{-11}</value><unit>meter^3 per kilogram second^2</unit></quantity> for <m>G</m>.</s> 
                    <s>Give your answer in <unit form="word/plural">day</unit> to two decimal places.</s>
                </p>
